<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-04-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-04-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="644" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d644">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Uhl</persName> to Sir
                                    <persName type="to">Julian Pauncefote</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-04-09"><hi rend="italic">April 9,
                                1895</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 73.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your note of the 1st instant, transmitting a copy of a
                            Canadian order in council, granting free entry into Canada to timber
                            booms imported from the United States.</p>
                        <p>The Department is much gratified that a reciprocal arrangement has thus
                            been effected between the United States and Canada in regard to the
                            matter in question.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Edwin F. Uhl</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>